caption: Three of four entrees were spot on though the rice noodles on one were stringy and felt like eating plastic.  I couldn't finish the dish though the fish was fine.  Service was mixed with attentive water refills yet our drinks needed two reminders and our kids drinks never came.  For the $200 bill for the four of us, I expect more.

Decent place to eat. The food was underwhelming. The spicy ahi was presented well but did not live up to the way it looked. The spring rolls were quite good as was the sashimi. The oysters, while delicious, were very small. Sad but tasty little oysters. The service here was excellent. We were seated quickly, the wait staff was quick and efficient, and the atmosphere was charming.
Great food and great service
Great experience. Welcoming, friendly staff and excellent comfort food. Pricey but worth it.

Roy Yamaguchi's signature restaurant in Honolulu is an amazing place to dine.  I had the lobster plantation paella, a caesar salad, and Mongolian BBQ ribs.  Others in our party had fresh fish with a variety of accompanying sauces.  For dessert, we all shared Roy's signature dessert: chocolate souffle with raspberry sauce and vanilla bean ice cream.  Everything was absolutely delicious!  The service was impeccable.  Dining tables were well spaced out to enforce social distancing, and the open design of the restaurant further gave us a sense of safety.  (All waitstaff were properly masked, as well.)  Everyone at our table thoroughly enjoyed our dinner  and the superb service that we received throughout our meal.  We look forward to returning again, soon!

The vibe is great and the food can be too. We started with the Crispy Brussel Sprouts and the Ume Glaze Pork Bao Buns. The sprouts were subtly flavored, I expected greater depth based on the ingredients... it was very good. The bao buns came deconstructed, I would have liked some sauce on the side as it too was subtly flavored. Entrees were a 16oz ribeye with vegetables and the highlight of the evening, truffled risotto. Kona Kampachi with stewed vegetables and a musubi was our other dish. We finished the evening with their signature melting chocolate souffle and the cookie and cream  cheesecake.  Why just four stars? Three of the dishes were overdone and I suspect it was due to the time dishes sat waiting.to be pickef up; I had a great view of the kitchen and observed this.

My wife on the other hand got a thin, rubbery, greasy fish that was not at all up to par. The rice that accompanied both dishes was just not good, mushy and very bland. This is an awesome place to eat--so much so that we went twice in a matter of days.  I have some significant dietary restrictions (allergies) that make it difficult to eat out. Usually when I tell servers about my restrictions, they are not received particularly well. Sometimes a server seems annoyed or irritated, but at best, they are hesitantly accommodating. Our server, Kimmie, was very understanding of my restrictions and treated my situation more like a fun challenge. Kimmie worked with the kitchen to figure out what I could eat and gave me a lot of great options for wonderful meals. The food was delicious and my date was thrilled that I was so happy—perhaps better described as giddy—so it was a big win for him as well.  In addition to Kimmie’s excellent service and the delicious food, I was so happy to have had the best old fashioneds I have had in a long time. I have them wherever I go and even try to make them myself. So when I get one that is well done, I’m floored. These old fashioneds were so amazing that we had several each and the bartender was kind enough to send out the recipe for me so I could try to recreate it at home.  A few nights later we hit the town again for dinner and decided that the only place we wanted to go was the Eating House. So we asked to have Kimmie again, and we had another wonderful night full of delicious food and cocktails.  The wait staff, kitchen, and bar staff helped me to have a safe night while enjoying delicious food. And even the management was great. Thanks for being a great restaurant that handles food allergies beautifully. You're awesome and I'll definitely be back if I'm ever in the area again. In the meantime....consider branching out to Colorado? :)

Needless to say, International Marketplace is unrecognizable, albeit some on the banyan trees neatly pruned and still holding dear to nostalgic days of old. So onto sharing about the Eating House. Casual dining in an open air but covered eatery. Prices are $$-$$$ but when you experience the flavorful combinations, that's what you'll remember the most. And if it's your birthday, you receive the most amazing panna cotta dessert ever! The flavors weren't overpowering each other. It was just yum! And so refreshing! For my next visit, I'm going to enjoy their take on the paella. Can't wait!
